{
  "In circuit analysis, Kirchhoff's laws can be written as a system Ax = b. What does the matrix A typically represent?": "",
  "The temperature of each component": "",
  "The power dissipation at each node": "",
  "The connectivity and impedance relationships of the circuit": "",
  "The voltage sources only": "",
  "In circuit analysis, the coefficient matrix A encodes Kirchhoff's current and voltage laws, incorporating the circuit's topology (connections) and component values (resistances, impedances). Solving Ax = b yields the unknown currents or voltages.": "",
  "A structural engineer solves Kd = F where K is the stiffness matrix, d is displacement, and F is the force vector. If K = [[4, -1],[-1, 4]] and F = (3, 6), what is d?": "",
  "(0.75, 1.5)": "",
  "(3, 6)": "",
  "(1, 2)": "",
  "(1.2, 1.8)": "",
  "det(K) = 16-1 = 15. K^(-1) = (1/15)[[4,1],[1,4]]. d = K^(-1)*F = (1/15)(4*3+1*6, 1*3+4*6) = (1/15)(18, 27) = (1.2, 1.8). The displacements are 1.2 and 1.8 units respectively.": "",
  "In control systems engineering, the state-space model is x' = Ax + Bu. What does the matrix A represent?": "",
  "The control signal, particularly regarding does in the": "",
  "The output matrix, particularly regarding time as": "",
  "The system dynamics matrix describing how the state evolves on its own": "",
  "The input matrix, particularly regarding stability based": "",
  "The A matrix (system matrix) describes the internal dynamics of the system -- how the state vector x changes over time in the absence of external input. Its eigenvalues determine the system's stability.": "",
  "For a control system to be stable, what must be true about the eigenvalues of the system matrix A?": "",
  "All eigenvalues must be zero": "",
  "The eigenvalues must all be real": "",
  "All eigenvalues must be positive": "",
  "All eigenvalues must have negative real parts": "",
  "For a continuous-time linear system x' = Ax to be stable (all solutions decay to zero), every eigenvalue of A must have a strictly negative real part. This ensures all modes decay exponentially rather than growing.": "",
  "In signal processing, the Discrete Fourier Transform (DFT) can be expressed as a matrix multiplication F*x. What kind of matrix is F?": "",
  "A random matrix, particularly regarding processing when": "",
  "A diagonal real matrix, particularly regarding expressed as": "",
  "A unitary matrix with entries involving complex exponentials (roots of unity)": "",
  "An upper triangular matrix when applying fundamental principles": "",
  "The DFT matrix F has entries F[j,k] = omega^(jk) where omega = e^(-2*pi*i/N). After normalization by 1/sqrt(N), it is unitary (F*F^dagger = I), meaning the transform preserves energy.": "",
  "A 3-node electrical circuit has the conductance matrix G = [[3,-1,-1],[-1,3,-1],[-1,-1,3]]. What is the sum of each row of G?": "",
  "0": "",
  "3": "",
  "1": "",
