  "The adjacency matrix of an undirected graph is always what type of matrix?": "",
  "Diagonal": "",
  "Skew-symmetric": "",
  "Symmetric": "",
  "Upper triangular": "",
  "The adjacency matrix of an undirected graph is symmetric because if node i is connected to node j, then j is also connected to i. Thus A[i,j] = A[j,i] for all i, j.": "",
  "What is a 'state-space model' in control engineering?": "",
  "A graph showing all possible system states": "",
  "A mathematical model using matrices to describe a system via x' = Ax + Bu and y = Cx + Du": "",
  "A model that only applies to space vehicles": "",
  "A model of the physical space a system occupies": "",
  "A state-space model represents a dynamic system with matrices: x' = Ax + Bu describes state evolution and y = Cx + Du describes the output. It compactly captures multi-input, multi-output system behavior using linear algebra.": "",
  "What is a 'stiffness matrix' in structural engineering?": "",
  "A matrix of material densities": "",
  "A matrix that measures the hardness of materials": "",
  "A matrix that only applies to rigid bodies": "",
  "A matrix K that relates applied forces to resulting displacements in a structure, via Kd = F": "",
  "The stiffness matrix K linearly maps displacement vectors d to force vectors F via F = Kd. It encodes how the structure resists deformation, and its properties (positive definiteness, symmetry) reflect physical stability.": "",
  "What does 'controllability' mean for a linear system x' = Ax + Bu?": "",
  "The system has a finite number of states": "",
  "The system always returns to equilibrium": "",
  "The ability to steer the system from any initial state to any desired state using the input u": "",
  "The input u can take any value": "",
  "A system is controllable if, for any initial and final states, there exists an input u(t) that drives the system between them in finite time. This requires the controllability matrix [B, AB, A^2B, ...] to have full rank.": "",
  "What does 'observability' mean for a linear system?": "",
  "All state variables can be directly measured": "",
  "The system can be observed physically": "",
  "The output is always positive": "",
  "The ability to determine the complete internal state from the output measurements alone": "",
  "A system is observable if the initial state can be uniquely determined from knowledge of the output y(t) over a time interval. This requires the observability matrix [C; CA; CA^2; ...] to have full rank.": "",
  "What is the 'transfer function' in engineering?": "",
  "The ratio of the output to the input in the frequency domain, encoding the system's input-output behavior": "",
  "The determinant of the system matrix": "",
  "The eigenvalues of the system matrix": "",
  "The function that transfers data between systems": "",
  "The transfer function H(s) = C(sI - A)^(-1)B + D relates the Laplace-transformed output to input. It captures the system's frequency response and is a rational function whose poles are the eigenvalues of A.": "",
  "What is the 'finite element method' (FEM)?": "",
  "A numerical technique that divides a structure into small elements, assembles element equations into a global matrix system, and solves it": "",
  "A method that only works for one-dimensional problems": "",
  "A technique for finding exact analytical solutions": "",
  "A method for counting the elements in a set": "",
  "FEM discretizes a continuous domain into finite elements, constructs local stiffness matrices for each element, assembles them into a global matrix equation, and solves the resulting linear system to approximate the solution.": "",
  "What is a 'Markov chain' in engineering and probability?": "",
  "A deterministic process with no randomness in most standard conditions": "",
  "A stochastic process where the next state depends only on the current state, described by a transition matrix": "",
  "Any sequence of random numbers, particularly regarding next within the typical range of values": "",
  "A chain of linked mechanical elements when measured under controlled conditions": "",
  "A Markov chain is a system that transitions between states probabilistically, where the probability of the next state depends only on the current state (memoryless property). The transition probabilities form a matrix whose columns sum to 1.": "",
  "What is a 'graph Laplacian' matrix?": "",
  "The inverse of the adjacency matrix": "",
  "The Laplacian differential operator applied to a graph": "",
  "L = D - A, where D is the degree matrix and A is the adjacency matrix of a graph": "",
  "The matrix of shortest paths between nodes": "",
  "The graph Laplacian L = D - A has diagonal entries equal to node degrees and off-diagonal entries equal to the negative of adjacency values. Its eigenvalues reveal graph connectivity, and it is used in network analysis and spectral clustering.": "",
  "What does 'BIBO stability' mean in control systems?": "",
  "Both inputs and outputs are binary": "",
  "The input and output have the same bounds": "",
  "The system has exactly two stable states": "",
  "Bounded-Input Bounded-Output: every bounded input produces a bounded output": "",
  "BIBO stability means that if every component of the input signal is bounded in magnitude, then every component of the output is also bounded. For linear time-invariant systems, this is equivalent to all poles of the transfer function having negative real parts.": "",
  "What is the 'condition number' of a matrix?": "",
  "The determinant of the matrix, particularly regarding large under equilibrium conditions": "",
  "The rank of the matrix, particularly regarding measures as observed in standard experiments": "",
  "The ratio of the largest to smallest singular value, measuring how sensitive the solution Ax = b is to perturbations": "",
  "The number of nonzero entries in the matrix under the given assumptions": "",
  "The condition number kappa(A) = sigma_max/sigma_min measures numerical sensitivity. A large condition number means small input changes can cause large output changes, making the system ill-conditioned for numerical computation.": "",
  "A civil engineer designs a two-span bridge modeled with stiffness matrix K = [[8, -3],[-3, 8]] and load vector F = (10, 5) kN. What are the nodal displacements d (in appropriate units)?": "",
  "(10, 5), particularly regarding": "",
  "(1.25, 0.625) when considering all": "",
  "(95/55, 70/55) approximately (1.727, 1.273)": "",
  "(2.0, 1.0), particularly regarding": "",
  "det(K) = 64 - 9 = 55. K^(-1) = (1/55)[[8,3],[3,8]]. d = (1/55)(8*10+3*5, 3*10+8*5) = (1/55)(95, 70) = (1.727, 1.273). The displacements are approximately 1.73 and 1.27 units respectively.": "",
  "An electrical engineer has a circuit with node voltages satisfying Gv = I, where G = [[5, -2],[-2, 5]] Siemens and I = (3, 6) Amperes. What are the node voltages?": "",
  "(3, 6), particularly": "",
