  "(0.6, 1.2) under equili": "",
  "(1, 2), particularly": "",
  "det(G) = 25-4 = 21. G^(-1) = (1/21)[[5,2],[2,5]]. v = (1/21)(5*3+2*6, 2*3+5*6) = (1/21)(27, 36) = (9/7, 12/7) approximately (1.286, 1.714) volts.": "",
  "A control engineer has a system with A = [[-2, 1],[0, -3]] and B = [[0],[1]]. She computes the controllability matrix C = [B, AB]. Is the system controllable?": "",
  "No, because B has a zero entry": "",
  "No, because A has negative eigenvalues": "",
  "Yes, but only if the eigenvalues are positive": "",
  "Yes, because rank(C) = 2 (full rank)": "",
  "AB = [[-2,1],[0,-3]]*[0,1]^T = [1,-3]^T. So C = [[0,1],[1,-3]]. det(C) = 0*(-3) - 1*1 = -1, which is nonzero, so rank(C) = 2 = n. The system is fully controllable.": "",
  "A web search engine models page importance using the PageRank algorithm, which uses a transition matrix M. After many iterations, the ranking converges to the eigenvector of M corresponding to which eigenvalue?": "",
  "Eigenvalue 0": "",
  "The smallest eigenvalue": "",
  "The most negative eigenvalue": "",
  "Eigenvalue 1 (the dominant eigenvalue)": "",
  "PageRank converges to the eigenvector of M with eigenvalue 1 (the Perron-Frobenius eigenvector). Since M is a column-stochastic matrix, 1 is its largest eigenvalue, and repeated multiplication drives any initial vector toward this steady-state distribution.": "",
  "A communications engineer uses a 2x2 MIMO channel matrix H = [[1, 0.5],[0.5, 1]] to transmit data. The singular values of H determine the channel capacities. What are the singular values of H?": "",
  "1 and 1": "",
  "2 and 0": "",
